Say hello to the world's largest sphere being built in Las Vegas right now. It's not quite done being built yet, but that's kinda the point of this. 

I took these pictures back in June, and I plan on doing a project update post in March while I am at CONEXPO 2023.

Anyway for those who don't know, this sphere will be a venue arena that can hold up to 20,000 people on its nine levels. It will apparently even have the largest LED screen in the world; among many other cool features and shops within its 875,000 square foot interior. 

That's cool and all, but the construction of this structure is the part I find most fascinating. For example, just to prepare this site for construction, first they had to move 110,000 cubic yards of dirt within the 18 acre site. 

To me that's really not that much dirt so let's talk about the real impressive part, which is the specific crane they're using to do all of the heavy lifting. 

@aecom brought in the world's 4th largest crane which was transported over the Atlantic ocean from Belgium to California. Once on North American soil it took 120 tractor trailers to transport to the site. 

The Demag CC-8800 took 18 days to assemble and stands 580 feet high with a max lift capacity of a staggering 1760 tons.

Pushing dirt is done best down hill...
.
.
.
@diesel_monkey_80_

The interesting part about this facility is that it isn't actually a traditional factory. It's an assembly center. 

Speaking of that, here's a couple Sany excavators at the end of the assembly line about to get decals, and some other final touches before they get shipped across North America to a dealership near you. 

The way I understand it is, instead of shipping an entire machine across seas on a boat with limited space during a world wide supply chain crisis. It's much easier, more efficient, and cheaper to ship the parts in containers and assemble the machines here in North America. Genius if you ask me.

On another note, I really enjoyed my private tour of @sanyamerica headquarters, but what I did at their testing grounds using a couple of their freshly assembled excavators equipped with machine control is what really had me excited. 

Shoutout to @leicageosystemsag for making this whole trip possible. More coming soon.

Over the past few months a couple of the creators here at Pushysix teamed up with @northern_boots to create some hilarious construction related content. 

On top of that, they have also been outfitting the Pushysix team with awesome work gear to keep us safe and comfortable on the job!

OMG THE ROBOTS ARE TAKING OVER 😱

As a person who clearly has a passion for operating, and has tried for years to represent and promote the skill of this trade to its highest level online. I have a couple things I wanna say about construction technology. 

First of all, let me say that there is a part inside of me that is extremely sad to see our art form of operating, and the need for our skills slowly fade away due to advancements in technology. 

However, I am smart enough to put the pieces together myself, and know how we got into this position, and understand what types of things that need to happen within our industry whether I want them or not. 

Over the past decade I have seen our work force shrink at a rapid rate mostly due to the boomer generation retiring and not teaching/helping the next generation enough to replace them. (My opinion)

There are obviously many other reasons, some of which are out of our control, but the fact is we now have a giant workforce gap in our industry. If you haven't already noticed manufacturers have been trying to compensate for this by making machines easier to operate by adding technology so less experienced people can fill the seats and half ass operate them. 

To wrap it up and get to my point. I do not see semi autonomy or even full autonomy for that matter as "they are trying to replace us". Rather I see it as just another way to try to fill our workforce gap; at least for the time being.
.
.
.

It makes me sick to my stomach seeing what is happening in our industry due to the labor shortages that we are all dealing with in construction.

I speak with owners of small to large size construction companies every other day, and often I hear about how they are unable to even bid on new work in some cases because they can’t find enough people to do the work.

In all honesty, it also makes me sick that I haven't tried to use more of my position and resources as much as I should have until recently to help more. Afterall construction did make me into who I am today, so its pretty much my duty.

That said, the team is assembled, and they have been focusing on finding new types of solutions to this problem-when I say solutions, I mean we have been testing crazy but effective "out of the box ways" to advertise blue collar job opportunities...and its working.

Based on our results I am confident we can help almost any company with recruitment issues ;)

If you're interested, click the link in the bio

WHAT'S NEXT FOR HITACHI?
By now we've all heard about the split between Hitachi and John Deere; well unless you've been living under a rock.

Anyway, for the last several months I've been thinking and trying to decide how a big change like this would impact the hitachi brand. I do know that globally they are a powerhouse, but I was seriously wondering if they'd even continue to exist in North America after this.

Like I've said in the past, Hitachi excavators have always been my favorite, even if most of them were disguised with a John Deere paint scheme for the last 20 years...

After stopping by their outdoor exhibit at Conexpo to see and film some stuff with their all new Dash 7 excavator lineup, a couple thoughts came to mind.

First of all, it occurred to me that for the last 20 years Hitachi(North America) hasn't been getting the credit(brand awareness) they deserve for their excavators here. John Deere basically reaped those benefits and I don't even blame them, because who knows maybe it was a necessary evil for both companies.

In addition to that, I believe the newly engineered Dash 7 excavators will do very well here on their own because their quality speaks for itself, just as it always has. Only this time they shall receive full credit.

Now I just have to operate one 🤪

IN CAB ALERT SYSTEM
Back when I was an operator, I would have loved to have a system like this to alert me inside the cab when ground workers or anyone for that matter would come up behind me or beside me while I was operating.

Just like many of you, I've done some pretty sketchy stuff in tight areas with people around because I didn't have a choice. 

As most of you know approaching heavy equipment is extremely dangerous not just because of the lack of vision (even with mirrors and back up cameras) because one of the things that makes a good operator, at least in my opinion is the ability to focus on a task. 

Even with nifty technology like this I still recommend throwing a clump of dirt in front of the operators line of sight and waiting for them to respond before approaching on foot. 

When an operator is focused or "in the zone" as I call it. We seem to notice much less in our peripheral vision so objects outside the side windows or in the back up cameras don't get our attention. 

I see many applications where the PA80 alert system by @leicageosystemsag
can and would come in handy where there is constant danger working with and around equipment in close quarters. 

Working around people requires an exhausting amount of focus, and I believe a system like this would relieve some operator fatigue. 

What do you guys think?

WHY USE A TRANSFER UNIT?
Well for those who don’t know much about paving. Stopping and starting the paver frequently can lead to abrupt changes in material flow and pave speed, contributing to bumps and sudden surges of material that can cause the paver to jerk or bounce, leading to uneven pavement. 

A transfer unit such as this @dynapac_north_america eliminates all of that by giving the paver a consistent flow of material, without the need of stopping so a dump truck can back right into the pavers hopper. Let me add it eliminates the risk of a truck bumping the paver all together.

So in other words. By providing a consistent and controlled material feed to the paver, the transfer unit helps the paver achieve a more uniform distribution of asphalt across the entire paving area. This obviously results in a smoother and more even pavement surface, which is the goal with every road. Everytime.

Who else is wishing @catconstruction would make a 349 Zero Swing?

Urban areas often have limited space for utility infrastructure, as we all know. Shared trenching optimizes the use of available space, leaving room for other essential infrastructure and amenities in our communities, such as pedestrian walkways, landscaping, and green spaces.

When planning for future growth and development, having water and sewer utilities located close to each other simplifies the process of extending these systems to new or the expansion of existing land developments for example. 

Constructing shared trenches is obviously much faster than excavating multiple trenches, and speeds up the installation process, reduces project cost, and minimizes disruptions to the surrounding area.

So while construction projects might cause temporary disruptions, they are often undertaken for long-term benefits such as improved infrastructure, enhanced safety, and increased efficiency. 

Let's not forget that most people focus on short-term inconveniences, which makes them (the general public) overlook these long-term gains.
.
.

Before a new operator is able to develop a feeling which most call "ass in the seat" that basically refers to the ability to feel slight movements or adjustments through the seat of a dozer. I have a little trick that helps in the meantime, and what most may use forever. 

Simply pick a reference point in your line of sight like the window sill, and line it up with the horizon or another horizontal line in the landscape of some kind. 

Start pushing level (without moving your head, changing your perspective), and if at any time the window sill reference point goes above your horizontal reference point it means the dozer is climbing and you need to compensate by putting the blade lower to keep level, and vice versa. 

Operating a dozer for the first time can be super frustrating but this should help you keep things level, instead of building unintended dirt bike jumps...Just remember a bulldozer is all about compensation. 
.
.
.

Say hello to the BLK2GO! This lidar scanner is designed to be lightweight and portable, allowing users to carry it easily and move around freely while scanning, just like I am doing. 

Sure @leicageosystemsag has other reality capture products but I specifically like this handheld version that makes it super easy for capturing data in various environments, even in hard to reach or confined spaces where traditional scanners might struggle to operate.

It's no wonder this 3D scanner is finding applications in various industries, including construction, architecture, engineering, archaeology, facilities management, and virtual reality, among others. 

It can be used for capturing as-built data, creating 3D models of buildings and structures, performing site surveys, and even generating virtual reality content.

Choosing between reality capture data and conventional survey points obviously depends on the specific needs of the project: 

For projects that require highly detailed and visual representations of the environment, reality capture data is a suitable option. 

For projects that demand high accuracy, legal compliance, and long-term stability, conventional survey points are necessary.
.
.
.

I realize I cannot be an expert at everything,  so that's why I hire people way better than me. 

Speaking of that, let's meet the creative director at Pushysix Media Group @pmg_travis 

He has worked for the team for over a year now, and during his time he has become an absolute asset to our business, as well as a good friend of mine. 

His background has nothing to do with construction, and that's exactly what makes him so great.

I recently caught up with @cr_excavating_ltd as a couple of their excavators were cleaning and maintaining some ditches that from what I learned, play a pivotal role in facilitating an unimpeded flow for stormwater and runoff towards the Fraser River in this area.

This practice proves to be extremely important not only during the winter months but also holds crucial implications for the summer season. 

As the channels are meticulously cleared, they serve as essential conduits, preventing obstruction and enabling efficient drainage of excess water.

Come summertime, these waterways undergo a strategic back flooding process from the Fraser River. 

This intentional flooding not only aids in replenishing groundwater but also serves a dual purpose by providing a valuable source of irrigation for the flourishing crops of farmers. 

Basically, keeping ditches clean and dealing with occasional floods is crucial for managing water well. It helps both farming and protecting the environment.

WEAR & ABRASION 
Due to the shape of dozer blades, some wear faster in areas than others...Obviously the "cutting edge and corner bits" experience the most abrasion and wear down the fastest. 

However, there are areas on the blade face, like the lower portion that experience a lot of wear due to extreme amounts of pressure that build up until the dirt is eventually forced upward. 

Because of this, it is common for the blade skin on the lower quarter or even lower half to get some extra armor to extend the life of the blade. 

This is usually done by welding plates/inserts onto the blade using such things as hardened steels like AR500 or HARDOX, or different compounds like chromium carbide, boron carbide,  and tungsten carbide. 

In many cases, a combination of these armor types may be used to provide comprehensive protection for bulldozers blades like this D11 blade.
